The aim of the study was to explore patients' views on the acceptability and feasibility of using color to describe osteoarthritis pain, and whether color could be used to communicate pain to healthcare professionals. Six group interviews were conducted with 17 patients with knee osteoarthritis. Discussion topics included first impressions about using color to describe pain, whether participants could associate their pain with color, how colors related to changes in pain intensity and different pain qualities, and whether they could envisage using color to describe pain to healthcare professionals. The group interviews indicated that, although the idea of using color was generally acceptable, it did not suit all participants as a way of describing their pain. The majority of participants chose red to describe high-intensity pain; the reasons given were because red symbolized inflammation, fire, anger, and the stop signal in a traffic light system. Colors used to describe the absence of pain were chosen because of their association with positive emotional feelings, such as purity, calmness, and happiness. A range of colors was chosen to represent changes in pain intensity. The SCL 90-R obsessive-compulsive dimension was not related to objective measures of attention, verbal memory, or age. Multivariate analyses indicated that reported symptoms of depression contributed 66% of the variance in predicting SCL 90-R obsessive-compulsive scores, whereas symptoms of anxiety contributed an additional 6% (P<.0001).

In this study, home blood pressure (BP) readings of 39 stroke patients were compared with the actual readings downloaded from the BP monitors. The study found that 90% of the home BP readings recorded in a booklet were exactly the same as the actual readings from the BP monitors. The mean difference in the systolic and diastolic BP readings between the booklet and monitor were 0.6 mmHg and 0.3 mmHg, respectively. The study concluded that home BP monitoring is reliable in stroke patients.

The study includes patients with metastatic carcinoma to cervical lymph nodes from an unknown head and neck primary origin. The treatment of these patients included radiotherapy with or without neck dissection. The study also compared the survival outcomes and patterns of failure in these patients who underwent neck dissection and those who underwent biopsy only. The results of the study showed no statistically significant difference in the 8-year overall survival and local relapse-free survival between the two groups. Therefore, there is not a need for neck dissection in these patients.

The study included both screen-detected (n = 53) and symptom-detected (n = 44) coeliac patients, with a median of 14 years since diagnosis, to compare their dietary compliance, quality of life, gastrointestinal symptoms and bone mineral density. The screen-detected patients were found to be asymptomatic in primary care and had normal or abnormal haematological findings, which led to coeliac serology testing. The study found that 96% of screen-detected and 93% of symptom-detected patients were adherent to a gluten-free diet. They also found that the screen-detected patients' quality of life and gastrointestinal symptoms were similar to those of the symptom-detected patients or non-coeliac controls and their bone mineral density was similar to that of the general population.

The study is about loss of consciousness and neuropsychological decrements after concussion. The study found that patients who had experienced traumatic loss of consciousness did not perform more poorly on neuropsychological testing than those with no loss of consciousness or uncertain loss of consciousness. All three groups demonstrated mildly decreased performance on formal tests of speed of information processing, attentional process, and memory.

The authors of this study report a correlation between the functional state of the heart of potential organ donors and the subsequent function of the transplanted heart. They performed transesophageal echocardiography (TEE) in 55 potential heart donors and evaluated the fractional area change (FAC), which is a measure of left ventricular function, and found that 20 of these potential donors had an FAC below 50%. They transplanted hearts from 40 of these donors and reported that 9 of these transplantations were not successful.

In PubMedQA-14745753, the authors evaluate the usefulness of half-dose contrast-enhanced 3D-MR angiography for depicting the abdominal aorta and its major branches. The authors assign 72 patients to one of four groups that undergo MR angiography after receiving different concentrations (original or diluted to 50%) and total amounts (single or half-dose) of gadolinium chelate injected at different rates (1 or 0.5 mL/second). The authors then calculate signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and contrast-to-noise ratio (CNR) of the abdominal aorta and of the common and external iliac arteries, and two blinded readers rate the respective image qualities. The authors found that the SNR and CNR of the abdominal aorta and the common iliac artery in the 0.5 mL/second groups were statistically significantly lower than those in the 1 mL/second groups. The difference in overall image quality across the four groups was not statistically significant.

The study enrolled 68 hemodialysis patients to evaluate their nutrition status using modified quantitative subjective global assessment (MQSGA). The relationship between malnutrition and arterial calcification was studied. In hemodialysis patients, the levels of serum albumin were negatively associated with calcification score and the expressions of BMP2 and MGP. While MQSGA score, serum phosphorus and calcium × phosphorus product showed positive relationships with calcification score and the expressions of BMP2 and MGP. However, the study did not find any significant difference in the expressions of BMP2 and MGP between the malnourished and well-nourished patients.

The authors of this study conducted a prospective cohort study of 176 patients with PMR, followed up for 5 years. Baseline factors associated with the duration of steroid therapy, the occurrence of relapses and the late development of GCA were identified using Cox regression and binary logistic regression.

The authors performed a study to evaluate the effect of open access publishing of scientific articles in intensive care medicine journals in terms of citations count. They compared citations count of non-open access articles with that of open access articles published in 2008 in Intensive Care Medicine. The authors found that open access articles had more citations than non-open access articles in the 30-35 months after publication, and the citation count was higher in the higher citation range (>8 citations). In addition, the authors found that the independent factors for citation advantage were the Hirsch index of the first signing author and open access status.

The authors investigated whether intraoperative precursor events are associated with postoperative major adverse events (MACE) in patients undergoing coronary artery bypass grafting, valve, and valve plus coronary artery bypass grafting. They defined precursor events as bleeding, difficulty weaning from cardiopulmonary bypass, repair or re-grafting, and incomplete revascularization or repair. The authors compared the frequency of these events in patients who had MACE to patients who did not have MACE. The authors found that a higher proportion of patients who had MACE had one or more of these precursor events compared to patients who did not have MACE. The authors concluded that these precursor events are associated with MACE.

The study compared ultrasound and X-ray in pediatric fracture diagnosis. The authors found that X-ray was superior to ultrasound for fracture type identification (80 correct results using X-ray, 66 correct results using ultrasound). However, ultrasound was superior to X-ray for dislocation identification (41 correct results using X-ray, 51 correct results using ultrasound). Both findings were not statistically significant after adjustment for multiple testing.

The study found that the model was feasible and that it led to positive outcomes, such as advance care planning conversations and the involvement of family in the process.

The study of this paper is about adult pharmacoresistant epilepsy patients treated with high doses of zonisamide. The study was conducted in Europe and focused on patients with epilepsy who were not controlled with more than two antiepileptic drugs. The study found that 55% of patients treated with zonisamide at a dose of more than 500 mg per day experienced a reduction in seizures of more than 50%. However, the study also found that 37% of patients experienced adverse events, such as drowsiness, vertigo, dizziness, and cognitive impairment. In addition, 66% of patients were already taking other antiepileptic drugs, and their plasma levels were normal or in the therapeutic range. Overall, the study suggests that high doses of zonisamide may be an effective and tolerable option for adult patients with pharmacoresistant epilepsy in Europe.

Schanz pin placement is a technique used in orthopaedic surgery to stabilize fracture sites in extremities. This study investigated the efficacy of ultrasonography in confirming Schanz pin placement and the interobserver repeatability of the ultrasound methodology. The study was conducted using four examiners who took measurements of Schanz pin protrusion beyond the distal cortices by ultrasonography and direct measurements post dissection. The measurements from both methods were compared, and it was found that ultrasonography underestimated Schanz pin protrusion length measurements by an average of 10%. The study also found that there was a proportional bias that increased as the magnitude of the pin protrusion increased. However, ultrasound data demonstrated good linear correlation with actual protrusion values in the 5 to 12 mm range. The interobserver repeatability analysis showed that all examiners were not statistically different in their measurements despite minimal familiarity with the ultrasound methodology.

The authors compared two techniques, NNSP and NNAP, in hypertrophied pig hearts. They found that with 100% LAD flow, both NNAP and NNSP maintained myocardial oxygenation, ATP, phosphocreatine, and inorganic phosphate at normal levels. When LAD flow was reduced to 50% of its control level, NNSP caused a significant decrease in myocardial oxygenation and phosphocreatine, whereas NNAP did not change these measurements significantly. With LAD flow further reduced to 20% of its control level, both NNAP and NNSP caused a significant decrease in myocardial oxygenation, ATP, and phosphocreatine, with an increase in inorganic phosphate. However, the changes were significantly greater during NNSP than during NNAP.

PubMedQA-22504515: The study was performed to evaluate the clinical and technical efficacy of endovenous laser ablation (EVLA) of small saphenous varicosities, particularly in relation to the site of endovenous access. Totally 59 patients with unilateral saphenopopliteal junction incompetence and small saphenous vein reflux underwent EVLA (810 nm, 14 W diode laser) with ambulatory phlebectomies. Small saphenous vein access was gained at the lowest site of truncal reflux. Patients were divided into 2 groups: access gained above mid-calf (AMC, n = 33) and below mid-calf (BMC, n = 26) levels. Outcomes included Venous Clinical Severity Scores (VCSS), Aberdeen Varicose Vein Questionnaire (AVVQ), patient satisfaction, complications, and recurrence rates. Both groups demonstrated significant improvement in VCSS, AVVQ, generic quality of life Short Form 36, and EuroQol scores

The purpose of the study was to evaluate whether blood oozing from a gingival crevice during routine periodontal examination can be used for determining glucose levels. Observational cross-sectional studies were carried out in 75 patients with chronic periodontitis who were divided into two groups: Group I and Group II, respectively. Blood oozing from the gingival crevices of anterior teeth following periodontal probing was collected with the stick of glucose self-monitoring device, and the blood glucose levels were measured. At the same time, finger-prick blood was taken for glucometric analysis and subsequent readings were recorded. The patient's blood glucose values ranged from 74 to 256 mg/dl. The comparison between gingival crevicular blood and finger-prick blood showed a very strong correlation, with a t value of 3.97 (at P value = 0.001).

If the patient is diagnosed with hydrocephalus, the next step is to determine the type of hydrocephalus. The method of choice for this is air-encephalography. However, the air-encephalography carries the risk of cerebral herniation. The study here proposes to use CT scans instead. The study suggests that the shape of the third ventricle can be used to determine the type of hydrocephalus. The authors found that if the third ventricle was rounded, the patient likely has non-communicating hydrocephalus. This suggests that CT scans can be used to determine the type of hydrocephalus, as long as the shape of the third ventricle is taken into account.

All other patients were submitted to surgery, independently of the response.

The effect of the moon phases was particularly relevant in multiparae and plurigravidae, where the mean day of delivery corresponded to the first or second day after the full moon.

Yes, increased carotid artery pulsatility and resistance indexes are early signs of vascular abnormalities in young obese males. The context states that the mean pulsatility index, resistance index, body mass index, waist circumference, systolic and diastolic blood pressure, homeostasis model assessment for insulin resistance, plasma fasting glucose, insulin, C-peptide, triglycerides, low-density lipoprotein cholesterol, and high-sensitivity C-reactive protein were statistically higher in obese subjects than in healthy controls. The instrumental activities of daily living (IADL) are a group of complex activities that include using the telephone, shopping, preparing meals, doing housework, doing laundry, using transportation, and handling money and personal care. They are related to social, physical, and cognitive functioning. In the PubMedQA-22188074 study, the authors investigated whether problems in IADL could add to conventionally used clinical measurements in helping to predict a dementia diagnosis at 1- and 2-year follow-ups.

This paper studies the effect of growth hormone treatment on mortality in adults with growth hormone deficiency (GHD). There are three groups of subjects: treatment group (n = 2229), primary (untreated) group (n = 109), and secondary control (partly treated) group (n = 356). The treatment group had 95 deaths, while the expected number of deaths was 74.6. The standardized mortality ratio (SMR) for the treatment group was 1.27 (95% confidence interval, 1.04–1.56). This indicates that the mortality of the treatment group was higher than the background population.

The text does not provide evidence of a systemic inflammatory response in pre-eclampsia. The authors analyzed the HELLP syndrome. This is a variant of pre-eclampsia. Pre-eclampsia is itself not a single disease, but a collection of conditions that can occur in pregnancy and are characterized by high blood pressure and signs of damage to other organs, such as the liver and kidneys. Pre-eclampsia is thought to be caused by abnormal blood vessel growth in the placenta.
